TITLE: Enqueueing a Faktory Job During User Signup (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to enqueue the 'postSignupTask' Faktory job after a user signup process, using the 'faktory-worker' Node.js client. It connects to the Faktory server, pushes the job with required task arguments, and closes the client connection. This service function expects a standard RedwoodJS service signature and requires access to Faktory connection details in environment variables. Proper error handling and closing of the client are best practices.
SOURCE: https://github.com/emelleby/docwood/blob/main/docs/content/04_how-to/background-worker.md#_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: JavaScript
CODE:
```
const faktory = require('faktory-worker')

export const signUp = async ({ input }) => {
  // Perform all the signup operations, such as creating an entry in the DB and auth provider
  // ...

  // The, send our task to the Faktory server
  const client = await faktory.connect()
  await client.job('postSignupTask', { ...taskArgs }).push()
  await client.close()
}
```

