TITLE: Accessing Raw Cache Client in RedwoodJS Service (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to access the underlying raw cache client (e.g., Redis or Memcached) directly within a RedwoodJS service function. This allows using specific client methods, like `MSET` shown here for setting multiple key-value pairs, that might not be exposed by the standard `cache()` or `cacheFindMany()` helpers. The example updates a post in the database and then explicitly sets two related cache entries using the imported `cacheClient` after stringifying the post data.
SOURCE: https://github.com/emelleby/docwood/blob/main/docs/content/03_reference/docs/services.md#_snippet_58

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
```javascript
import { cacheClient } from 'src/lib/cache'

export const updatePost = async ({ id, input }) => {
  const post = await db.post.update({
    data: input,
    where: { id },
  })
  // highlight-next-line
  await cacheClient.MSET(
    `post-${id}`,
    JSON.stringify(post),
    `blogpost-${id}`,
    JSON.stringify(post)
  )

  return post
}
```
```

